# Rcts

```
## Overview
Randomized Controlled Trials (RCTs) are a form of experimentation used to test new ideas, approaches, and interventions in a controlled and iterative manner.

## Purpose
The purpose of RCTs is to establish causal relationships between variables by systematically testing new solutions against existing ones, allowing for evidence-based decision-making and the scaling up of successful interventions.

## How it works
RCTs involve randomly assigning participants to an experimental or control group, where one group receives a new solution (e.g. re-usable nappy) and the other group receives a standard solution (e.g. disposable nappy). Data is collected over a set period, allowing researchers to measure the effectiveness of the new solution.

## Requirements
Research and data collection skills are necessary for effective use of RCTs. Activities must occur in a controlled environment with access to resources such as funding, personnel, and equipment.

## Reflections
RCTs require careful consideration of factors such as sample size, participant selection, and potential biases. It is essential to ensure that the control group is not influenced by the experimental group, and vice versa.

## Related methods (if any)
Experimentation

## License
Free or open

## Examples
The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) has used RCTs to test sustainable solutions to single-use diapers in Eswatini.
```
